HB 1037 Reengrossed 2026 Regular Session Bourriaque
Abstract: Modifies certain procedures to reform operations within the Dept. of
Transportation and Development and provide for the creation and duties of the chief
operating officer.
Present law (R.S. 36:502(A)(1)) specifies that the secretary, undersecretary, deputy
secretary, assistant secretary of project delivery, commissioner of multimodal commerce,
and assistant secretary of operation are officers of the Dept. of Transportation and
Development (DOTD).
Proposed law adds the chief operating officer as an officer within the DOTD.
Present law (R.S. 36:502(A)(2)) requires that the secretary, undersecretary, deputy secretary,
assistant secretary of project delivery, assistant secretary of operations, executive director
of the Offshore Terminal Authority, commissioner of multimodal commerce, and such other
positions which may be authorized by the State Civil Service Commission or the state
constitution be unclassified positions in the DOTD.
Proposed law adds the chief operating officer as an unclassified position within the DOTD.
Present law (R.S. 36:502(B)) prohibits any person serving as a secretary, undersecretary,
deputy secretary, assistant secretary of project delivery, assistant secretary of operations,
commissioner of multimodal commerce, or in any other office in the DOTD to receive any
additional salary from the state other than that salary which he receives by virtue of serving
in any one of such offices.
Proposed law adds the chief operating officer as a person prohibited from receiving any
additional salary from the state.
Present law (R.S. 36:503) provides for the appointment, duties, and responsibilities of the
secretary of the DOTD. Requires that the secretary be the executive head and chief
administrative officer of the DOTD. Specifies that the secretary is responsible for the
policies of the dept., except as specifically provided for particular agencies transferred to or
placed within the dept. by other provisions of present law.
Proposed law removes the requirement that the secretary serve as the chief administrative
officer of the DOTD.
Present law (R.S. 36:505(A)) provides for the appointment, duties, and responsibilities of
the deputy secretary of the DOTD, appointed by the governor, and serves as the appointing
authority for the office of transformation. Further requires that the duties and functions of
the deputy secretary be to oversee the office of transformation to optimize the DOTD and
those otherwise assigned by the secretary.
Proposed law adds an additional duty and function of the deputy secretary to serve as the
chief administrative officer of the office of transformation.
Present law (R.S. 36:505(B)) specifies that if the position of the deputy secretary is not filled
during the absence of the secretary, the secretary may designate either the undersecretary or
the assistant secretary of project delivery to serve as acting secretary in his absence.
